    profile_image_url: null,
    cover_image_url: null,
    biography: `Eleanor Marie Thompson was a force of nature wrapped in grace. Born in the heart of Charleston during the height of World War II, she grew up in a world that taught her resilience, compassion, and the power of education.

From an early age, Eleanor showed an insatiable curiosity about the world. While other children played with dolls, she collected books. Her parents, both educators themselves, nurtured this love of learning, creating a home filled with literature, music, and passionate dinner table debates about everything from philosophy to politics.

Eleanor attended Spelman College in Atlanta, where she majored in English Literature and minored in Music. It was there that she found her voice—not just as a scholar, but as an advocate for civil rights. She participated in sit-ins, organized voter registration drives, and used her gift for words to write essays that appeared in local papers, calling for justice and equality.

After graduating summa cum laude in 1964, Eleanor moved to Boston to pursue her Master's degree in Education at Harvard. It was in a small jazz club in Cambridge that she met James Thompson, a young architect with dreams as big as hers. They married in 1966, beginning a 52-year partnership that would see them raise three children, build successful careers, and remain each other's greatest champions.

Eleanor dedicated 40 years to teaching high school English. But to call her simply a teacher would be a grave understatement. She was a mentor, a guide, a challenger of minds. Her classroom was a sanctuary where students learned not just about Shakespeare and Dickinson, but about themselves. She had an extraordinary gift for seeing potential in young people that they couldn't yet see in themselves.

She pushed her students to think critically, to question assumptions, to write with honesty and courage. Former students would often return years later to tell her that she changed their lives. Her response was always the same: "I didn't change anything. I just helped you see what was always there."

Beyond the classroom, Eleanor was deeply involved in her community. She served on the boards of three non-profits focused on literacy and education. She volunteered at the local library every Saturday morning, reading to children and helping adults learn to read. She organized an annual poetry slam that became a Boston institution, giving young poets a platform to share their work.

Eleanor loved jazz music—Ella Fitzgerald, Miles Davis, John Coltrane were constant companions in her home. She was an accomplished pianist herself, though she rarely played for anyone outside her family. Sunday mornings often began with her at the piano, filling the house with music while James made breakfast.

She was an avid gardener, transforming their small backyard into a haven of roses, tomatoes, and herbs. She believed that working with the earth kept you humble and grateful. She was a voracious reader who always had at least three books going at once—usually one classic, one contemporary novel, and one collection of poetry.

But above all, Eleanor was a woman who lived her values. She believed in the power of words, the importance of education, the necessity of fighting for justice, and the transformative power of love. She believed that every person had a story worth telling, and she spent her life helping others find their voice to tell it.

In her final years, even as illness slowed her body, her mind remained sharp and her spirit undiminished. She continued to write, to read, to mentor. She passed away peacefully at home, surrounded by her family, with a book of Mary Oliver's poetry on her nightstand and jazz playing softly in the background.

Eleanor Marie Thompson lived 81 years, and in that time, she touched thousands of lives. She was a teacher, a mother, a grandmother, a friend, a advocate, an artist. But more than any title, she was a light—and that light continues to shine through all the lives she illuminated.`,
